{"type":"message","id":"761a6e09","parentId":"fd135042","timestamp":"2026-03-26T11:58:53.972Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_04d485256d6844a0a97c6b90","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"WiFi 6 7 PHY physical layer 802.11ax 802.11be specification technical overview\",\n  \"provider\": \"tavily\",\n  \"count\": 5,\n  \"tookMs\": 1733,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"tavily\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fcf3d9bfda3911af\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nWi-Fi 6 (802.11ax) Technical Guide - Cisco Meraki Documentation\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fcf3d9bfda3911af\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://documentation.meraki.com/Wireless/Design_and_Configure/Architecture_and_Best_Practices/Wi-Fi_6_(802.11ax)_Technical_Guide\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"9044a7f9b6c54df9\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n802.11ax Feature Overview ; Physical Layer (PHY). High Throughput (HT). Very High Throughput (VHT) ; Operating Bands. 2.4 and 5 GHz. 5 GHz only.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"9044a7f9b6c54df9\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.999943\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2949b087a5f575eb\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nUnderstanding Wi-Fi 4/5/6/6E/7/8 (802.11 n/ac/ax/be/bn)\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"2949b087a5f575eb\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.wiisfi.com/\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"8f2f82f1833b3884\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nPHY: PHY is an abbreviation for physical. For example, 'PHY speed' refers to the physical speed at the raw network layer. For every Wi-Fi device, there is\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"8f2f82f1833b3884\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.99984276\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"278140d4013011a2\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n[PDF] Key Technologies for IEEE 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) White Paper\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"278140d4013011a2\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://dl.cdn-anritsu.com/zh-tw/test-measurement/files/Brochures-Datasheets-Catalogs/White-Paper/wi-fi7-er1100.pdf\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"278188eecec70688\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nTable 1: Scope of 802.11 Standard Layer OSI Reference Model 802.11 Standard 7 Application Out of scope 6 Presentation Out of scope 5 Session Out of scope 4 Transport Out of scope 3 Network Out of scope 2 Data Link Out of scope (Logic Link Control) Medium Access Control (MAC) 1 Physical Physical (PHY) Table 2: Major Differences Between 802.11ax and 802.11be Layer Main Candidate Features 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6/6E) 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) MAC Multi-band and multichannel aggregation and operation (Multi-link) Not supported New feature (On the table) Enhanced link adaptation and retransmission protocol Not supported New feature (On the table) Multi-Access Point (AP) coordination Not supported New feature (On the table) PHY Resource Unit Single RU Multiple RU Channel width (max.) 160 MHz 320 MHz Subcarrier modulation (max.) 1024QAM 4096QAM Spatial stream (max.) 8 streams 16 streams * These candidate features are described in the Spec Framework Document.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"278188eecec70688\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.99942076\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"07b9115983ada744\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nOverview of Wi-Fi 7 (IEEE 802.11be) - MATLAB & Simulink\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"07b9115983ada744\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.mathworks.com/help/wlan/ug/overview-of-wifi-7-or-ieee-802-11-be.html\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"15f0352a2ef52544\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nThe fundamental objective of Wi-Fi 7 is to provide extremely high throughput, ensure deterministic low latency, and enhance network capacity that can support a minimum throughput of 30 Gb/s at the access point (AP), which is four times the rate of IEEE 802.11ax™ or Wi-Fi 6, across carrier frequencies ranging from 2.401 GHz to 7.125 GHz. Compared to Wi-Fi 6, the Wi-Fi 7 standard increases channel bandwidth to 320 MHz, boosts throughput and capacity with 4K-QAM modulation, and brings in new features like MLO and channel efficiency improvements such as preamble puncturing support for single user (SU) transmissions. To address this, Wi-Fi 7 introduces MLO capability, a combined framework that manages multiple links, optimizing resource use across them. * The introduction of MLO significantly enhances coordinated operations across multiple links, offering a stark contrast to the traditional, isolated operations over multiple bands in existing Wi-Fi technologies. The Wi-Fi 7 standard introduces a unified framework for managing multiple links through the concept of a multilink device (MLD). Therefore, Wi-Fi 7 introduces an improved version of single-radio MLD, called *Enhanced multi-link single-radio (EMLSR)*.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"15f0352a2ef52544\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.9987649\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"a628fcd4b2e14820\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nIEEE 802.11ax: The Sixth Generation of Wi-Fi White Paper - Cisco\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"a628fcd4b2e14820\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/wireless/white-paper-c11-740788.html\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"75af6e54473ded90\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nIEEE 802.11ax OFDMA technology lets even first-wave 802.11ax access points support eight spatial streams and deliver up to 4800 Mbps at the physical layer,\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"75af6e54473ded90\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.9932025\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"WiFi 6 7 PHY physical layer 802.11ax 802.11be specification technical overview","provider":"tavily","count":5,"tookMs":1733,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"tavily","wrapped":true},"results":[{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fcf3d9bfda3911af\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nWi-Fi 6 (802.11ax) Technical Guide - Cisco Meraki Documentation\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fcf3d9bfda3911af\">>>","url":"https://documentation.meraki.com/Wireless/Design_and_Configure/Architecture_and_Best_Practices/Wi-Fi_6_(802.11ax)_Technical_Guide","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"9044a7f9b6c54df9\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n802.11ax Feature Overview ; Physical Layer (PHY). High Throughput (HT). Very High Throughput (VHT) ; Operating Bands. 2.4 and 5 GHz. 5 GHz only.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"9044a7f9b6c54df9\">>>","score":0.999943},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2949b087a5f575eb\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nUnderstanding Wi-Fi 4/5/6/6E/7/8 (802.11 n/ac/ax/be/bn)\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"2949b087a5f575eb\">>>","url":"https://www.wiisfi.com/","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"8f2f82f1833b3884\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nPHY: PHY is an abbreviation for physical. For example, 'PHY speed' refers to the physical speed at the raw network layer. For every Wi-Fi device, there is\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"8f2f82f1833b3884\">>>","score":0.99984276},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"278140d4013011a2\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n[PDF] Key Technologies for IEEE 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) White Paper\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"278140d4013011a2\">>>","url":"https://dl.cdn-anritsu.com/zh-tw/test-measurement/files/Brochures-Datasheets-Catalogs/White-Paper/wi-fi7-er1100.pdf","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"278188eecec70688\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nTable 1: Scope of 802.11 Standard Layer OSI Reference Model 802.11 Standard 7 Application Out of scope 6 Presentation Out of scope 5 Session Out of scope 4 Transport Out of scope 3 Network Out of scope 2 Data Link Out of scope (Logic Link Control) Medium Access Control (MAC) 1 Physical Physical (PHY) Table 2: Major Differences Between 802.11ax and 802.11be Layer Main Candidate Features 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6/6E) 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) MAC Multi-band and multichannel aggregation and operation (Multi-link) Not supported New feature (On the table) Enhanced link adaptation and retransmission protocol Not supported New feature (On the table) Multi-Access Point (AP) coordination Not supported New feature (On the table) PHY Resource Unit Single RU Multiple RU Channel width (max.) 160 MHz 320 MHz Subcarrier modulation (max.) 1024QAM 4096QAM Spatial stream (max.) 8 streams 16 streams * These candidate features are described in the Spec Framework Document.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"278188eecec70688\">>>","score":0.99942076},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"07b9115983ada744\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nOverview of Wi-Fi 7 (IEEE 802.11be) - MATLAB & Simulink\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"07b9115983ada744\">>>","url":"https://www.mathworks.com/help/wlan/ug/overview-of-wifi-7-or-ieee-802-11-be.html","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"15f0352a2ef52544\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nThe fundamental objective of Wi-Fi 7 is to provide extremely high throughput, ensure deterministic low latency, and enhance network capacity that can support a minimum throughput of 30 Gb/s at the access point (AP), which is four times the rate of IEEE 802.11ax™ or Wi-Fi 6, across carrier frequencies ranging from 2.401 GHz to 7.125 GHz. Compared to Wi-Fi 6, the Wi-Fi 7 standard increases channel bandwidth to 320 MHz, boosts throughput and capacity with 4K-QAM modulation, and brings in new features like MLO and channel efficiency improvements such as preamble puncturing support for single user (SU) transmissions. To address this, Wi-Fi 7 introduces MLO capability, a combined framework that manages multiple links, optimizing resource use across them. * The introduction of MLO significantly enhances coordinated operations across multiple links, offering a stark contrast to the traditional, isolated operations over multiple bands in existing Wi-Fi technologies. The Wi-Fi 7 standard introduces a unified framework for managing multiple links through the concept of a multilink device (MLD). Therefore, Wi-Fi 7 introduces an improved version of single-radio MLD, called *Enhanced multi-link single-radio (EMLSR)*.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"15f0352a2ef52544\">>>","score":0.9987649},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"a628fcd4b2e14820\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nIEEE 802.11ax: The Sixth Generation of Wi-Fi White Paper - Cisco\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"a628fcd4b2e14820\">>>","url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/wireless/white-paper-c11-740788.html","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"75af6e54473ded90\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nIEEE 802.11ax OFDMA technology lets even first-wave 802.11ax access points support eight spatial streams and deliver up to 4800 Mbps at the physical layer,\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"75af6e54473ded90\">>>","score":0.9932025}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774526333967}}
